# Vibe Coding Rules (12 Rules by Andrej Karpathy)

These rules define how you should approach every coding task in this project.
They are based on Andrej Karpathy's full Vibe Coding Handbook (12 rules).
Read and apply them before generating or modifying any code.

## Philosophy

### Rule 1: You Own All Code
You must fully own every line of code you commit. Understand it, test it, and
take responsibility for its performance. If LLM-generated code exceeds your
understanding, do not use it. LLMs are accelerators, not crutches.

### Rule 2: Keep It Minimal
Start with the simplest implementation and add complexity only when clearly
needed. Build the MVP first, iterate later. No speculative features.

### Rule 3: Comment-Driven Development
Show the LLM an example of the desired output first, then guide it with clear
comments. Write the comments as if you were explaining the logic to a colleague.

### Rule 4: Full-Context Map, Piece-by-Piece Build
First, write the entire program structure as a comment outline (full-context map).
Once the map is correct, fill in each function/module one at a time.

## Interaction & Debugging

### Rule 5: Make the LLM Retell First
Before asking the LLM to modify code, require it to read and explain what the
code does. Confirm understanding before making changes.

### Rule 6: Review Diffs, Question Every Change
Inspect every diff the LLM produces. Understand why each line was changed.
Do not blind-accept changes. Remove leftover debug comments and unused code.

### Rule 7: Enter “Teaching Mode”, Not “Fixing Mode”
When encountering a bug, do not just throw error messages at the LLM.
First explain your debugging process, assumptions, and investigation path.
You are teaching the LLM about your code, not asking it to fix a bug.

### Rule 8: 0→1 with LLM, 1→N by Hand
Let the LLM generate the initial implementation (0→1), then you take over
the final 20%: edge cases, error handling, performance tuning. When you start
justifying "why this was written this way", stop and write it yourself.

## Coding & Tools

### Rule 9: Version Control Is Your Safety Net
Commit frequently. After every small functional chunk the LLM completes, commit.
This lets you easily roll back when the next change goes wrong.

### Rule 10: Test-Driven Vibe Coding
Before asking the LLM to write implementation, make it write unit tests and
integration tests first. Use test cases as the way to communicate requirements:
"Here are the APIs, here are the expected inputs/outputs. Write tests first,
then the implementation."

### Rule 11: Enhance LLM Context with Tools
Use IDE-integrated tools (Claude Code, Cursor, Code Buddy) that automatically
provide project context, file structure, and type definitions. Reduce the
amount of manual context you need to supply.

### Rule 12: Avoid Infinite Loops
Set a time/attempt limit. If the LLM fails to fix a bug after 3 consecutive
attempts, stop. Re-analyze the problem, provide more context, simplify the
reproduction case, then continue.